        <item xml:id="womanServant">
          <term>Woman (Servant)</term>
          <desc type="editorial">For someone described as  ‘X’s woman’, where the term indicates a female servant. Note that this term should not be used for people of particularly high status (those given the title ‘Mrs’ and above). Within the casebooks we find two overlapping but distinct senses of ‘servant’ (and related terms): an older sense in which society is hierarchical and everyone serves someone else all the way up to the monarch; and a newer sense in which the term ‘servant’ denotes a person doing a particular low-status job. To deal with these different meanings of the term, we use the <gi>relation</gi> <val>servant</val> for service at all levels of society, but do not use the <gi>occupation</gi>s ‘Servant’, ‘Woman (Servant)’, or similar, for high-status people. Thus if an entry describes Mrs X as Lady YZ’s woman, then the <gi>relation</gi> <val>servant</val> should be used to link them but the <gi>occupation</gi> ‘Woman (Servant)’ omitted</desc>
